[normal]The killings of Mohammed 
[normal]Saleem
[normal] and Drummer Lee Rigby in April and May 2013 were both investigated as terrorism by the police.  Suspects have been charged with murder in each case.
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Detention of 
[normal]undeportable
[normal] foreign nationals in 
[normal]Belmarsh
[normal] (Anti-Terrorism Crime and Security Act 2001), replaced in turn by control orders (Prevention of Terrorism Act 2005) and TPIMs (Terrorism Prevention and Investigation Measures Act 2011).
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Particularly in the Terrorism Act 2006: see my report 
[normal]The Terrorism Acts in 2011
[normal], June 2012, 
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Such measures may also encourage the terrorists.  As Jonathan Evans of MI5 said in 2010: “
[normal]In recent years we appear increasingly to have imported from the American media the assumption that terrorism is 100% preventable and that any incident that is not prevented is seen as a culpable government failure.  This is a nonsensical way to consider terrorist risk and only plays into the hands of the terrorists themselves.
[normal]” 
[normal]Ayman
[normal] al-
[normal]Zawahiri
[normal], the current leader of al-Qaida, confirmed the point in a recent message marking the 12
[normal]th
[normal] anniversary of 9/11: “
[normal]We must bleed America economically by provoking it, so that it continues its massive expenditures on security
[normal].”  
[normal] 
